718512f-a.title: Manhattan: Central Park West - 94th Street
718512f-a.text:
Central Park West, 95th to 94th Streets. (Before Reconstruction).
President Borough of Manhattan.
March 22, 1920.
718512f-a.folder: Central Park West & 94th Street, Manhattan, NY

718511f-a.title: Manhattan: Central Park West - 94th Street
718511f-a.text:
(1)
Central Park West, west side, north from 94th Street. In the background at the S.W. corner of 96th Stroet is the Scotch Presbyterian Chuch, and beyond it, on the N.W. corner is the
First Church of Christ Scientist.
Note the torn-up condition of the street, due to construction
work on the Eighth Avenue subway.
May 31, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, three months later, showing the work of demolition in process. "The Towers," on the N.W. corner of 94th Street, is the last building to go. A sixteen-story apartment building will occupy this entire block, and two more will rise in the next block, one at 3 West 95th Street and one on the site of
the Scotch Presbyterian Church.
September 10, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.

718510f-a.title: Manhattan: Central Park West - 94th Street
718510f-a.text:
Central Park West at N.W. corner of 94th Street, where 'The Towers'
has just been demolished.
October 23, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
718510f-a.folder: Central Park West & 94th Street, Manhattan, NY

718519f-a.title: Manhattan: Central Park West - 94th Street
718519f-a.text:
Central Park West, west side, from 94th to 96th Streets, seen from Central Park, the Scotch Presbyterian Church on the S.W. corner of 95th Street being hidden by the tree in the right of the picture. The apartment building on the N.W. corner of 94th Street is The Towers; the two in the middle of the block are "Fillmore" and "Flavia"; they date from the 1890's. The only buildings visible in the next block are the old house on the N.W. corner of 95th Street and the little chapel adjoining it at 3 west 95th Street.
May 31, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same scene, the following winter. All the buildings on Central Park West from 94th to 95th Streets have been demolished, and a 16-story apartment building is under construction in their place. A new 16-story apartment building is under construction at 3 West 95th Street, and another on the S.W. corner of 96th Street, where the Scotch Presbytenian Church stood. The small houses, 351-55 Central Park West, remain standing; 351, on the N.W. corner of 95th Street, is
visible in both pictures.
February 2, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
